# Transform to Structure Data Type

Here are the transformations in different programming languages:

## **C/C++**

```c
#include <stdio.h>

struct Person {
    char name[50];
    int age;
    float height;
};

int main() {
    struct Person person = {"John", 40, 1.87};

    printf("Name: %s\n", person.name);
    printf("Age: %d\n", person.age);
    printf("Height: %.2f\n", person.height);

    return 0;
}
```

## **Python**

```python
from collections import namedtuple

# Using namedtuple
Person = namedtuple('Person', ['name', 'age', 'height'])
person = Person(name="John", age=40, height=1.87)

print(f"Name: {person.name}")
print(f"Age: {person.age}")
print(f"Height: {person.height}")
```

Or with **dataclass**:
```python
from dataclasses import dataclass

@dataclass
class Person:
    name: str
    age: int
    height: float

person = Person("John", 40, 1.87)
print(f"Name: {person.name}, Age: {person.age}, Height: {person.height}")
```

## **Java**

```java
class Person {
    String name;
    int age;
    double height;

    Person(String name, int age, double height) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
        this.height = height;
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Person person = new Person("John", 40, 1.87);
        System.out.println("Name: " + person.name);
        System.out.println("Age: " + person.age);
        System.out.println("Height: " + person.height);
    }
}
```

## **JavaScript**

```javascript
const person = {
    name: "John",
    age: 40,
    height: 1.87
};

console.log(`Name: ${person.name}`);
console.log(`Age: ${person.age}`);
console.log(`Height: ${person.height}`);
```

---

**Key Benefits:**
✅ Better code organization  
✅ Type safety (in statically typed languages)  
✅ Improved readability  
✅ Easier maintenance

