# Transform to Structure Data Type

Here's how to transform the given code to use a structure data type:

## **C/C++ Implementation:**

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

struct Person {
    char name[50];
    int age;
    float height;
};

int main() {
    struct Person person;

    strcpy(person.name, "John");
    person.age = 40;
    person.height = 1.87;

    printf("Name: %s\n", person.name);
    printf("Age: %d\n", person.age);
    printf("Height: %.2f\n", person.height);

    return 0;
}
```

## **Python Implementation:**

```python
from collections import namedtuple

# Using namedtuple
Person = namedtuple('Person', ['name', 'age', 'height'])
person = Person("John", 40, 1.87)

print(f"Name: {person.name}")
print(f"Age: {person.age}")
print(f"Height: {person.height}")
```

## **Java Implementation:**

```java
class Person {
    String name;
    int age;
    float height;

    Person(String name, int age, float height) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
        this.height = height;
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Person person = new Person("John", 40, 1.87f);

        System.out.println("Name: " + person.name);
        System.out.println("Age: " + person.age);
        System.out.println("Height: " + person.height);
    }
}
```

## **Key Benefits:**

✓ **Organized data** - Related fields grouped together  
✓ **Reusability** - Define once, use multiple times  
✓ **Readability** - Clear variable associations  
✓ **Maintainability** - Easy to modify and extend

# Transform Code to Use Structure Data Type

Here are several ways to transform this code using structure data types:

## **1. C/C++ Struct**
```c
#include <stdio.h>

struct Person {
    char name[50];
    int age;
    float height;
};

int main() {
    struct Person person = {"John", 40, 1.87};

    printf("Name: %s\n", person.name);
    printf("Age: %d\n", person.age);
    printf("Height: %.2f\n", person.height);

    return 0;
}
```

## **2. Python (Using Class/Named Tuple)**
```python
from collections import namedtuple

# Using namedtuple
Person = namedtuple('Person', ['name', 'age', 'height'])
person = Person("John", 40, 1.87)

print(f"Name: {person.name}")
print(f"Age: {person.age}")
print(f"Height: {person.height}")
```

## **3. Python (Using Class)**
```python
class Person:
    def __init__(self, name, age, height):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age
        self.height = height

person = Person("John", 40, 1.87)

print(f"Name: {person.name}")
print(f"Age: {person.age}")
print(f"Height: {person.height}")
```

## **4. JavaScript (Using Object)**
```javascript
const person = {
    name: "John",
    age: 40,
    height: 1.87
};

console.log(`Name: ${person.name}`);
console.log(`Age: ${person.age}`);
console.log(`Height: ${person.height}`);
```

## **5. Java (Using Class)**
```java
public class Person {
    private String name;
    private int age;
    private double height;

    public Person(String name, int age, double height) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
        this.height = height;
    }

    // Getters
    public String getName() { return name; }
    public int getAge() { return age; }
    public double getHeight() { return height; }
}

// Usage
Person person = new Person("John", 40, 1.87);
```

**Choose based on your programming language!** Each approach organizes related data into a single, reusable structure.

# Transform Code to Use Structure Data Type

Here are the transformations in different programming languages:

## **C Language**
```c
#include <stdio.h>

struct Person {
    char name[50];
    int age;
    float height;
};

int main() {
    struct Person person = {"John", 40, 1.87};

    printf("Name: %s\n", person.name);
    printf("Age: %d\n", person.age);
    printf("Height: %.2f\n", person.height);

    return 0;
}
```

## **C++**
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

struct Person {
    string name;
    int age;
    float height;
};

int main() {
    Person person = {"John", 40, 1.87};

    cout << "Name: " << person.name << endl;
    cout << "Age: " << person.age << endl;
    cout << "Height: " << person.height << endl;

    return 0;
}
```

## **Java**
```java
class Person {
    String name;
    int age;
    float height;

    Person(String name, int age, float height) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
        this.height = height;
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Person person = new Person("John", 40, 1.87f);

        System.out.println("Name: " + person.name);
        System.out.println("Age: " + person.age);
        System.out.println("Height: " + person.height);
    }
}
```

## **Python (Using dataclass)**
```python
from dataclasses import dataclass

@dataclass
class Person:
    name: str
    age: int
    height: float

person = Person("John", 40, 1.87)

print(f"Name: {person.name}")
print(f"Age: {person.age}")
print(f"Height: {person.height}")
```

## **Python (Using NamedTuple)**
```python
from typing import NamedTuple

class Person(NamedTuple):
    name: str
    age: int
    height: float

person = Person("John", 40, 1.87)

print(f"Name: {person.name}")
print(f"Age: {person.age}")
print(f"Height: {person.height}")
```

## **JavaScript**
```javascript
const person = {
    name: "John",
    age: 40,
    height: 1.87
};

console.log("Name: " + person.name);
console.log("Age: " + person.age);
console.log("Height: " + person.height);
```

Choose the language based on your requirement! Each approach maintains the structure and organization of related data.
